Besides the incidents below this overall is an ok place. Because of my love for banyas I visit them at least once a week regularly since 2017, visited all Chicago area banyas as many outside US, and familiar with what a great one should look like. At this place there are definitely things that can be improved like: - cold plunge water gets dirty if there are more people in there, and it gets over chlorinated (burns your eyes, nose and skin), but most of the time its cold as it should be. - Turkish room is the best here, but russian room is too dry and too hot, more humidity and less temperature would make it better.  ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- December 2020 experience: greedy practices: through selective choice of COVID19 rules: like they stop having drinking water, and shut down the drinking water fountain because "it's unsafe and against the code", but to sell bottled water, and keep all sauna facilities (except the restaurant) open "is safe and by the code" - let's call it what it is - greed and abuse of situation.  ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- Initial 2018 review: I am a often visitor there so saw the sauna with different levels of attendance, and I would give them closer to 3.5 stars, but yesterday I got poisoned from their mussels dish in restaurant, I think it was from broth in it, it was really salty and I tried to leave most of it in the plate, I didn't get food poisoned for many years and would not expect from a place like this to get it. So sorry guys, I will live you a better review next time, but getting poisoned was sub-par experience.  On other visits noticed the drain smelling steam room in men's part (and they get insulted if you tell them that, telling that they cleaned it, I believe they did but it doesn't smell any better, that's why its almost all the time empty, not many people could bare the smell).

I love this #Russian #bathhouse and try to visit monthly for a #platza and #bodyscrub. The service is incredible and restorative. First we get our locker keys, then go downstairs to the #baths. There is a bathtub-hot #pool large enough to swim back and forth a length, with jets and shower overhead, and a sub-freezing #saltwater pool. Then there is a #steamroom, and a #Turkish #sauna, where begins the Platza. First there is a cool towel over your head, and the Platza guy, Vasily, whips you (basically gently) with leafy branches that smell great, back and front. It feels great, especially in the cold winter months. Then comes a tap-cold shower, which is much less pleasant... but not as cold as the saltwater pool, that Vasily gladly jumps right into. Once you have your breath back, the body scrub. This is like being in a car wash machine, and feels wonderful in addition to making your skin glow. The atmosphere is very comfortable, there are reclining couches and places to sit down and rest, in between bathing and sauna sessions and while waiting for your turn at the Platza. You can order food and drinks brought down to you while you wait - Red Square has excellent #Baltic and #Russian food, and a great #beer and #vodka selection. Upstairs there is a full service #dayspa and #restaraunt with full #bar. The #lamb is particularly good. My one caveat - Be comfortable with nudity... swimsuits are optional and not particularly popular.

Honestly I've been going to this place for years and I was very disappointed with my last visit. Not only did they change the rates, but the girl who was servicing us at the desk was not very friendly and she also wasn't very informative. I had called over the phone to make an appointment for two people to get 30 minute massages she told us that smallest time frame that we can book for would be 45 minutes. When we got there we saw the signs that straight up say 30 minute massage for $35, my girlfriend and I both said we wanted the $35 massage and that we had to change our appointment because that's what we were requesting over the phone. We told them that we wanted the Swedish massage her massage Tech ended up giving her a deep tissue without asking which cost her an additional $15. I thought this was unprofessional. Also during my massage although his intentions were sweet, my masseuse answered a phone call and then completed text messages while in my massage. It was anything but relaxing and I left there hurting more than feeling rejuvenated. I also feel like even though he said he stop the time clock I didn't get my 30 minutes, I also said that my neck was bothering me but I wanted to focus mainly on my lower back he did worked on my neck for 12 minutes which was almost half of the booking and then he talks through the entire thing about business which was literally the last thing I wanted to discuss during my massage. He was a really sweet guy and he took the phone call because it was his girlfriend's birthday and he was getting something delivered to her and they needed instructions however I feel like if he had something that busy going on you should have said to us how about you go down to the spa for 30 minutes and then come back up and I'll be ready for you. In the past Spa entry is free if you pay for a service, I have been going there since 2014 with that same understanding but yesterday they charged us an additional 1750 to utilize the spa area we were there for less than an hour and a half before we decided we had to leave. The locker my friend was assigned  would not lock for her , and my locker once closed would not reopen , I even spoke with a staff member upfront to express that we were having issues and instead of offering to change us to new lockers and helping us they said oh we'll take a look at it later. Which never ended up happening, I ended up fighting with the locker for about 15 minutes to get it open myself. There was dirty Band-Aid floating in the hot tub as well as a huge green stain of dead skin cells that we had been floating on top of the tub and spoiled over onto the stone that had dried there it was bogus, it seems that the saunas were also really dirty because the towels that we were sitting on in the saunas which normally come out clean we're stained by the wood, the two of us shared one clean towel to dry off once we showered because are towels looked disturbing. The blow dryer in the women's section barely works and if I'm going to spend over $50 for the day I should be able to blow dry my hair properly, instead I left with wet hair because the blow-dryer kept smoking and I thought it was going my hair on fire. I'm really disappointed because I Love This Spa I love that it has its own restaurant, and I'd love to continue supporting it however based on my last trip I don't know when the next time I'll be back. It was really disappointing.

I want to begin by thanking the staff here because the customer service provided at Red Square Spa has always been amazing. Edward is definitely a strong asset on the team, not only for the way he serves and bartends, but for being respectful, easy to talk to, and for having an overall positive attitude. The design of the restaurant portion of the upstairs is a replica of the inside of a room in an Eastern European train; I felt as if I were travelling from Kyiv to Lviv! As for the food, Red Square definitely has one of the best tasting borschts in Chicago. Also, their shishkabobs, Ukrainian salo, and cake Napoleon were appetizing. I look forward to coming back and enjoying the sauna, food, and inviting atmosphere!

I've been here twice. Very unique, but relaxing and decadent experience. I have been to Russia once and this place is filled with reminders from my trip. Please take a moment to look at the photos of the food I have posted. Every bite, delicious and clearly prepared with care. I can't post the bath house area photos as pictures are prohibited, but there are varying levels or heat and cold with massages and scrubs available for a little extra. The sensation of going from a scorching steam sauna to an ice bath is indescribable and invigorating. The whole evening with bath access and food cost me around $85 (I was the designated driver), but drinking is allowed in the bath lounge area. Mind you, you can spend the entire day there and even take a nap. To dive into another culture without the actual travel is difficult, but this place allows you to vanish from Chicago into Russia.

Overall: Authentic, unique, and effective! I came out a new man and slept like a log that night. What an experience!  The good: They offer a variety of packages, including the traditional platza services (we didn't indulge). There are also a variety of rooms and the temperatures turned up high! There are wet, dry, and steam rooms, plus whirlpools and a cold bath. All are effective and felt great in their own way, and the spaces are large and fit plenty of people. Upstairs they have a good amount of (some traditional, some not) food and drinks for you to have, and the passes you buy last all day. We all got the vodka flights to go along with our food (thus negating the sweating).  The not-so-good: Felt dirty at times downstairs in the spa/saunas, only a 2 towel quota, and the atmosphere isn't as authentic as I would've hoped. It's a pretty typical spa/sweat kind of place, but I thought it'd be a little more...character. That said, the dining room and bar area had a good ambiance. The waitress got our vodka flight orders wrong, which means we had the best first and the worst last. Lastly, the place is a tad pricey...  Atmosphere: 8/10 Service: 8/10 Food: 8/10

Technically 3.5, but I'm being generous since I had such a good time.  I'm a big fan of Korean-style saunas and get myself to one whenever possible. However, on a recent trip to Chicago a friend suggested I try this place since it is much closer to where I'm staying than King Spa. I'll give anything a try once, and I'd been meaning to check out a Russian-style spa.  The entrance fee here is a reasonable $30, cut in half to $15 on Mondays and Tuesday if you purchase a service. I decided on a deep tissue massage since I was very stressed and very much needed it. First we went down to the spa area.  Red Square is a decent size, though it can only accommodate a couple dozen women in total and when there were around 10 in there at one time the place felt somewhat crowded. We came on a Monday, so that wasn't a problem most of our time there.  There's a hot tub, a steam room that smells of mint, a Turkish steam sauna made from cedar wood that's very hot and mildly steamy, and a Russian sauna that gives you a drier heat. The steam room and hot tub are pretty small and can only fit 3 - 4 women at once.  I enjoyed the heat level of the hot tub and that there are two powerful water jets that shoot a concentrated stream of water down that feels akin to a massage on the muscles. Really nice. Unfortunately, women do not observe the "Takje a shower before you go into hot tub" rule, and so I saw stuff floating in said water which did not make me want to spend a long time in there. Contrast this with Korean spas where such a thing hardly ever happens as the staff is quite diligent.  I think the nakedness optional vibe is partly to blame. Go full Monty, ladies!  There was one shower that poured freezing cold water down on you, which I loved. This made it possible to go in the Turkish sauna room, which otherwise felt overwhelmingly hot when you first go in.  The steam room smelled amazing, but whenever the steam spigot came on it was SUPER loud and, if you are sitting in the wrong spot, it shoots steam right at your legs. One poor girl leapt up when it turned on and nearly fell she was so startled.  The 30 minute deep tissue massage I got was AMAZING. The guy worked on my jaw and upper back/shoulders and I felt so relaxed when he was done. Then I went back to the warmth of the hot tub and steam room to relax my poor, battered muscles. I even fell asleep at one point. All this meant that I didn't have much residual pain later on or the next day. I just felt rejuvenated.  Love the food in the restaurant. It's a little odd to go up there in a robe knowing that folks might be just in there not having come for the sauna but instead for the food.  I do prefer the Korean way of things but would not object to coming to Red Square again. Loved my time there and it melted away a lot of stress.

Of course, I had to check out the Russian bath house in the city.  There was a groupon deal for admission.  I think it was $15 for robes and everything.  The actual spa/salon, etc has a lot of parts to it.  There is a restaurant, nail salon, facial/massage area then you go downstairs to the locker room.  In the female locker room, there is a steam room, sauna, hot tub, showers and toilets.  Anyway, we did the traditional Russian thing.  I cant remember the name.  It consisted of going into the hot sauna area and having a lady hit you with a eucalyptus leaf.  Yes, you heard me right.  It was HOT in there.  She had to be dying.  Next was a salt scrub and then lotion and massage.  The whole thing took about 35 mins.  I think it was $55, plus 15% tip.  Not terrible...but King Spa is so much cheaper.  PROS In the city for the folk that dont like to go outside of Chicago You can wear a bathing suit!  If you are uncomfortable walking around naked, this might be the place for you.  Now, clothing is optional so others may be in their bday suits...but you dont have to. Alcohol that you can order and get it brought down to you.  Kind of interesting because most people go to detox.  HA Food if you are hungry...we didnt eat anything so I dont know if its any good Salt scrub felt amazing Lotion and massage after was amazing.  It felt like she was slathering warm Crisco all over my body Easy street parking Lots of different services-nails, facials, massage, tanning, etc Steam room smelled of eucalyptus Staff was nice and helpful  CONS Small area Expensive (when compared to King Spa, my favorite little bath house) I wasnt a fan of the hot eucalyptus leaf beating...but maybe you will be  For me, it would do in a pinch, but I prefer King Spa.
